Hamburg: Voss Verlag.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1906, &ldquo;Einf&uuml;hlung und
&Auml;sthetischer Genu&szlig;&rdquo;, <em>Die Zukunft</em>, 16:
100&ndash;114.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1907, &ldquo;Das Wissen von Fremden
Ichen&rdquo;, <em>Psychologische Untersuchungen</em>, 1:
694&ndash;722.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1912/13, &ldquo;Zur Einf&uuml;hlung,&rdquo;
<em>Psychologische Untersuchungen</em>, 2: 111&ndash;491.</li>

<li>MacKenzie, C. and S. Sorial, 2022, &ldquo;The Empathy Dilemma:
Democratic Deliberation, Epistemic Injustice, and the Problem of
Empathic Imagination&rdquo;, <em>Res Publica</em>, 28:
365&ndash;389.</li>

<li>Maibom, H., 2005, &ldquo;Moral Unreason: The Case of
Psychopathy,&rdquo; <em>Mind and Language</em>, 20:
237&ndash;257.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, &ldquo;The Presence of Others&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 132: 161&ndash;190.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009, &ldquo;Feeling for Others: Empathy,
Sympathy, and Morality&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 52:
483&ndash;499.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash; (ed.), 2014, <em>Morality and Empathy</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, &ldquo;Psychopathy: Morally
Incapacitated Persons&rdquo;, in Th. Schramme and S. Edwards (eds.),
<em>Handbook of the Philosophy of Medicine</em>, Berlin/New York:
Springer, pp. 1131&ndash;1144.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, <em>The Space Between: How Empathy
Really Works</em>, New York: Oxford University Press</li>

<li>Makkreel, R., 2000. &ldquo;From Simulation to Structural
Transposition: A Diltheyan Critique of Empathy and Defense of
<em>Verstehen</em>&rdquo;, in H.H. K&ouml;gler and K. Stueber (eds.),
<em>Empathy and Agency: The Problem of Understanding in the Human
Sciences</em>, Boulder: Westview Press, pp. 181&ndash;193.</li>

<li>Marsh, A., 2014. &ldquo;Empathy and Moral Deficits in
Psychopaths,&rdquo; in <em>Empathy and Morality</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press, pp. 138&ndash;154.</li>

<li>Matravers, D., 2018, &ldquo; The Object of Empathic
Emotions,&rdquo; in D. Matravers and A. Waldow (eds.),
<em>Philosophical Perspectives on Empathy: Theoretical Approaches and
Empirical Challenges</em>, New York: Routledge, 60&ndash;73.</li>

<li>May, J., 2018, <em>Regard for Reason in the Moral Mind</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>May, L., M. Friedman, and A. Clark, 1996, <em>Mind and
Morals</em>, Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</li>

<li>McGeer, V., 2008, &ldquo;Varieties of Moral Agency: Lessons from
Autism,&rdquo; in W. Sinnott-Armstrong (ed.), <em>Moral
Psychology</em> (Volume 3), Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press,
227&ndash;248.</li>

<li>Mead. G.H., 1934, <em>Mind, Self, and Society</em>, Chicago:
University of Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Mehrabian, A., and N. Epstein, 1972, &ldquo;A Measure of Emotional
Empathy&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Personality</em>, 40:
525&ndash;543.</li>

<li>Mehrabian, A., A.L. Young, and S. Sato, 1988, &ldquo;Emotional
Empathy and Associated Individual Differences&rdquo;, <em>Current
Psychology</em>: <em>Research and Review</em>, 7: 221&ndash;240.</li>

<li>Meltzoff, A., and R. Brooks, 2001. &ldquo;&lsquo;Like Me&rsquo; as
a Building Block for Understanding Other Minds: Bodily Acts,
Attention, and Intention,&rdquo; in B. Malle, L. Moses, and D. Baldwin
(eds.), <em>Intentions and Intentionality</em>, Cambridge, MA: MIT
Press, 171&ndash;191.</li>

<li>Meyers, D. T. 2017, &ldquo;A Modest Feminist Sentimentalism:
Empathy and Moral Understanding Across Social Difference&rdquo;, in R.
Debes and K. Stueber (eds.), <em>Ethical Sentimentalism: New
Perspectives</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp.
210&ndash;229.</li>

<li>Morrell, M., 2010, <em>Empathy and Democracy: Feeling, Thinking
and Deliberation</em>, University Park: Penn State University
Press.</li>

<li>Nichols, S., 2001, &ldquo;Mindreading and the Cognitive
Architecture underlying Altruistic Motivation&rdquo;, <em>Mind &amp;
Language</em>, 16: 425&ndash;455.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2004, <em>Sentimental Rules: On the Natural
Foundation of Moral Judgment</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>Nagel, T., 1974, &ldquo;What Is It Like to Be a Bat?&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Review</em>, 83(4): 435&ndash;450.</li>

<li>Nichols, S., and S. Stich, 2003, <em>Mindreading</em>, Oxford:
Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Neuberg, S.L., R. Cialdini, S.L. Brown, C. Luce, and B. Sagarin,
1997, &ldquo;Does Empathy Lead to Anything More Than Superficial
Helping?&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Personality and Social Psychology</em>
73: 510&ndash;516.</li>

<li>Nussbaum, M., 2001, <em>Upheavals of Thought: The Intelligence of
Emotions</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Oxley, J.C., 2011, <em>The Moral Dimensions of Empathy: Limits and
Applications in Ethical Theory and Practice</em>, Basingstoke:
Palgrave Macmillan.</li>

<li>Paul, L.A. 2014, <em>Transformative Experience</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020, &ldquo;Who Will I Become&rdquo;, in
E. Lambert and J. Schwenkler (eds.), <em>Becoming Someone New: Essays
on Transformative Experiences, Choice, and Change</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press, pp. 16&ndash;36.</li>

<li>Persson, I., and J. Savulescu, 2018, &ldquo;The Moral Importance
of Reflective Empathy&rdquo;, <em>Neuroethics</em>, 11:
183&ndash;193.</li>

<li>Petraschka, T. and C. Werner, 2024, <em>Empathy&rsquo;s Role in
Understanding Persons, Literature, and Art</em>, London and New York:
Routledge.</li>

<li>Prandl, A., 1910, <em>Die Einf&uuml;hlung</em>, Leipzig: Verlag
von Johann Ambrosius Barth.</li>

<li>Preston, S., and F. de Waal, 2002a, &ldquo;Empathy: Its Ultimate
and Proximate Bases&rdquo;, <em>Behavioral and Brain Sciences</em>,
25: 1&ndash;72.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2002b, &ldquo;Communications of Emotions
and the Possibility of Empathy in Animals&rdquo;, in S. Post, L.
Underwood, J. Schloss, and W. Hurblut (eds.), <em>Altruism and
Altruistic Love: Science, Philosophy, and Religion in Dialogue</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp. 284&ndash;308.</li>

<li>Prinz, J., 2011a, &ldquo;Is Empathy Necessary for Morality?&rdquo;
in A. Coplan and P. Goldie (eds.), <em>Empathy: Philosophical and
Psychological Perspectives</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
211&ndash;229.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011b, &ldquo;Against Empathy&rdquo;,
<em>The Southern Journal of Philosophy</em>, 49 (Spindel Supplement):
214&ndash;233.</li>

<li>Ravenscroft, I., 1998, &ldquo;What is it Like to be Someone Else?
Simulation and Empathy&rdquo;, <em>Ratio</em>, 11: 170&ndash;185.</li>

<li>Read, H., 2021, &ldquo;Empathy and Common Ground&rdquo;,
<em>Ethical Theory and Moral Practice</em>, 24: 1&ndash;15.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;When and Why to Empathize with
Political Opponents&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 180(3):
773&ndash;793.</li>

<li>Rhodes, M. and L. Chalik, 2013, &ldquo;Social Categories as
Markers of Intrinsic Interpersonal Obligations&rdquo;,
<em>Psychological Science</em>, 26: 999&ndash;1006.</li>

<li>Rifkin, J., 2009, <em>The Empathic Civilization: The Race to
Global Consciousness in a World in Crisis</em>, New York:
Tarcher/Penguin.</li>

<li>Rizzolatti, G., and L. Craighero, 2004, &ldquo;The Mirror Neuron
System&rdquo;, <em>Annual Review Neuroscience</em>, 27:
169&ndash;192.</li>

<li>Rizzolatti, G. and C. Sinigaglia, 2008, <em>Mirrors in the Brain:
How our Minds Share Actions and Emotions</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;The Mirror Mechanism: A Basic
Principle of Brain Function,&rdquo; <em>Nature Review
